<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="21" type="clarification">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">Clarification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
The original illustrations and descriptions deserve some clarifications. Antennae are certainly of about the same length, but they are not tapered but digitate, and surpass the tips of palps, at least the right one (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Sigambra wassi Pettibone, 1966 A holotype (USNM 30988), anterior region, dorsal view B same, right lateral view C same, frontal view D paratype (USNM 30987), posterior region, dorsal view E same, posterior end. Scale bars: 0.6 mm (A, C), 0.9 mm (B), 0.5 mm (D), 0.2 mm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/361268" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
). The pharynx is fully exposed, and the basal ring has about 20 irregular hemispherical lobes, but the anterior margin is eroded and damaged (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Sigambra wassi Pettibone, 1966 A holotype (USNM 30988), anterior region, dorsal view B same, right lateral view C same, frontal view D paratype (USNM 30987), posterior region, dorsal view E same, posterior end. Scale bars: 0.6 mm (A, C), 0.9 mm (B), 0.5 mm (D), 0.2 mm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/361268" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
), such that its marginal papillae are difficult to detect; there are vague indications of the presence of approx. eight large papillae (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Sigambra wassi Pettibone, 1966 A holotype (USNM 30988), anterior region, dorsal view B same, right lateral view C same, frontal view D paratype (USNM 30987), posterior region, dorsal view E same, posterior end. Scale bars: 0.6 mm (A, C), 0.9 mm (B), 0.5 mm (D), 0.2 mm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/361268" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
). They would include some round projections which might represent the eroded base of papillae, or that they were collapsed when the specimen was compressed into the container.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
The posterior end is twisted in the paratype. It had to be pressed by a glass slide in order to have a better observation of the pygidium and anal cirri (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Sigambra wassi Pettibone, 1966 A holotype (USNM 30988), anterior region, dorsal view B same, right lateral view C same, frontal view D paratype (USNM 30987), posterior region, dorsal view E same, posterior end. Scale bars: 0.6 mm (A, C), 0.9 mm (B), 0.5 mm (D), 0.2 mm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/361268" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11">Fig. 11D</figureCitation>
). Anal cirri are delicate, three times longer than pygidial width and tapered (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Sigambra wassi Pettibone, 1966 A holotype (USNM 30988), anterior region, dorsal view B same, right lateral view C same, frontal view D paratype (USNM 30987), posterior region, dorsal view E same, posterior end. Scale bars: 0.6 mm (A, C), 0.9 mm (B), 0.5 mm (D), 0.2 mm (E)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/361268" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.893.39594.figure11">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
), not subcylindrical as originally illustrated.
</paragraph>
